308
00:14:23.800 --> 00:14:27.500
And speaking it, he wistlylooked on me

309
00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:31.000
as who should say, "Iwould thou wert the man

310
00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
that would divorce thisterror from my heart,"

311
00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:35.900
meaning the king atPomfret.

312
00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:39.930
Come, let's go.

313
00:14:39.930 --> 00:14:43.130
I am the king's friend andwill rid his foe.

314
00:14:55.730 --> 00:15:00.230
I have been studying how Imay compare

315
00:15:00.230 --> 00:15:04.600
this prison where I liveunto the world.

316
00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:08.400
And for because the worldis populous

317
00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:15.030
and here is not a creaturebut myself, I cannot do it.

318
00:15:18.030 --> 00:15:20.230
Yet I'll hammer it out.

319
00:15:22.270 --> 00:15:28.000
My brain I'll prove thefemale to my soul,

320
00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.770
my soul the father,

321
00:15:30.770 --> 00:15:37.000
and these two beget ageneration of stillbreeding thoughts,

322
00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:42.770
and these same thoughtspeople this little world

323
00:15:42.770 --> 00:15:45.500
in humors like the peopleof this world,

324
00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:47.930
for no thought iscontented.

325
00:15:49.430 --> 00:15:56.500
The better sort, asthoughts of things divineare intermixed

326
00:15:56.500 --> 00:16:00.770
with scruples and do setthe word itself againstthe word.

327
00:16:01.970 --> 00:16:06.270
As thus, "Come, littleones."

328
00:16:06.270 --> 00:16:11.270
And then again, "It is ashard to come as for a camel

329
00:16:11.270 --> 00:16:15.400
to thread the postern of asmall needle's eye."

330
00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:23.870
Thoughts tending toambition, they do plotunlikely wonders--

331
00:16:23.870 --> 00:16:26.100
how these vain weak nails

332
00:16:26.100 --> 00:16:29.330
may tear a passage throughthe flinty ribs

333
00:16:29.330 --> 00:16:34.270
of this hard world, myragged prison walls.

334
00:16:34.270 --> 00:16:39.370
And, for they cannot, diein their own pride.

335
00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:51.600
Thoughts tending tocontent flatter themselves

336
00:16:51.600 --> 00:16:54.630
that they are not thefirst of fortune's slaves,

337
00:16:54.630 --> 00:16:57.730
nor shall not be the last.

338
00:16:57.730 --> 00:17:01.770
Like silly beggars who,sitting in the stocks,

339
00:17:01.770 --> 00:17:03.130
refuge their shame,

340
00:17:03.130 --> 00:17:06.530
that many have and othersmust sit there.

341
00:17:08.030 --> 00:17:11.970
And in this thought theyfind a kind of ease,

342
00:17:11.970 --> 00:17:14.600
bearing their ownmisfortunes on the back

343
00:17:14.600 --> 00:17:17.570
of such as have beforeendured the like.

344
00:17:20.570 --> 00:17:25.970
Thus play I in one personmany people,

345
00:17:25.970 --> 00:17:29.030
and none contented.

346
00:17:29.030 --> 00:17:33.800
Sometimes am I king.

347
00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:37.730
Then treasons make me wishmyself a beggar,

348
00:17:37.730 --> 00:17:40.070
and so I am.

349
00:17:40.070 --> 00:17:45.530
Then crushing penurypersuades me I was betterwhen a king.

350
00:17:45.530 --> 00:17:48.800
Then am I kinged again,

351
00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:53.300
and by and by think that Iam unkinged by Bolingbroke

352
00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:55.600
and straight am nothing.

353
00:17:59.130 --> 00:18:01.800
But whate'er I be,

354
00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:06.630
nor I nor any man that butman is,

355
00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:09.800
with nothing shall bepleased

356
00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:13.030
till he be eased withbeing nothing.

357
00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:19.800
Music do I hear?

358
00:18:26.430 --> 00:18:28.130
Oh, keep time.

359
00:18:29.930 --> 00:18:31.630
How sour sweet music is

360
00:18:31.630 --> 00:18:34.770
when time is broke and noproportion kept.

361
00:18:36.830 --> 00:18:39.300
So is it in the music ofmen's lives.

362
00:18:41.100 --> 00:18:44.700
And here have I thedaintiness of ear

363
00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:47.800
to cheque time broke in adisordered string,

364
00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:52.500
but for the concord of mystate and time

365
00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:57.200
had not an ear to hear mytrue time broke.

366
00:18:57.200 --> 00:19:03.030
I wasted time, and nowdoth time waste me.

367
00:19:03.030 --> 00:19:06.330
For now hath time made mehis numbering clock.

368
00:19:06.330 --> 00:19:08.270
My thoughts are minutes.

369
00:19:08.270 --> 00:19:11.230
And with sighs they jartheir watches on untomine eyes,

370
00:19:11.230 --> 00:19:12.400
the outward watch,

371
00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:14.700
whereto my finger, like adial's point,

372
00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:17.600
is pointing still, incleansing them from tears.

373
00:19:17.600 --> 00:19:20.300
Now, sir, the sound thattells what hour it is

374
00:19:20.300 --> 00:19:23.330
are clamorous groans thatbeat upon my heart,

375
00:19:23.330 --> 00:19:25.070
which is the bell.

376
00:19:25.070 --> 00:19:31.970
So sighs and tears andgroans show minutes,times, and hours.

377
00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:41.230
But my time runs posting onin Bolingbroke's proud joy,

378
00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:44.330
while I stand fooling here,his Jack o' the clock.

379
00:19:44.830 --> 00:19:47.700
This music mads me!

380
00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:50.230
Let it sound no more!

381
00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:52.600
For though it have holpmadmen to their wits,

382
00:19:52.600 --> 00:19:57.070
in me it seems it willmake wise men mad.

383
00:20:07.070 --> 00:20:09.570
Yet blessing on his heartthat gives it me,

384
00:20:12.170 --> 00:20:14.000
for 'tis a sign of love.

385
00:20:15.900 --> 00:20:22.630
And love to Richard is astrange brooch in this allhating world.

386
00:20:26.830 --> 00:20:28.870
Hail, royal prince.

387
00:20:28.870 --> 00:20:31.670
Thanks, noble peer.

388
00:20:31.670 --> 00:20:35.400
The cheapest of us is tengroats too dear.

389
00:20:40.170 --> 00:20:42.500
What art thou?

390
00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:43.570
And how comest thou hither

391
00:20:43.570 --> 00:20:46.070
where no man never comesbut that sad dog

392
00:20:46.070 --> 00:20:48.230
that brings me food tomake misfortune live?

393
00:20:49.700 --> 00:20:52.130
I was a poor groom of thystable, king,

394
00:20:52.130 --> 00:20:53.930
when thou wert king,

395
00:20:53.930 --> 00:20:55.230
who, traveling towardsYork,

396
00:20:55.230 --> 00:20:57.530
with much ado at lengthhave gotten leave

397
00:20:57.530 --> 00:21:00.100
to look upon my sometimesroyal master's face.

398
00:21:01.400 --> 00:21:03.270
Oh, how it yearned myheart

399
00:21:03.270 --> 00:21:06.400
when I beheld in Londonstreets that coronation day

400
00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:09.200
when Bolingbroke rode onroan Barbary,

401
00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:11.770
that horse that thou sooften hast bestrid,

402
00:21:11.770 --> 00:21:13.830
that horse that I socarefully have dressed.

403
00:21:13.830 --> 00:21:16.830
Rode he on Barbary?

404
00:21:16.830 --> 00:21:19.570
Tell me, gentle friend,how went he under him?

405
00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:22.670
So proudly as if hedisdained the ground.

406
00:21:22.670 --> 00:21:27.270
So proud that Bolingbrokewas on his back.

407
00:21:27.270 --> 00:21:31.530
That jade hath eat breadfrom my royal hand.

408
00:21:31.530 --> 00:21:34.900
This hand hath made himproud with clapping him.

409
00:21:34.900 --> 00:21:36.870
Would he not stumble?

410
00:21:36.870 --> 00:21:39.970
Would he not falldown, since pride musthave a fall,

411
00:21:39.970 --> 00:21:43.130
and break the neck of thatproud man that did usurphis back?

412
00:21:46.070 --> 00:21:47.070
Forgiveness, horse.

413
00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:49.300
Why do I rail on thee,

414
00:21:49.300 --> 00:21:53.700
since thou, created to be awedby man, wast born to bear?

415
00:21:56.470 --> 00:21:59.830
I was not made a horse,

416
00:21:59.830 --> 00:22:03.170
and yet I bear the burdenlike an ass,

417
00:22:03.170 --> 00:22:07.730
spurred, galled, and tiredby jouncing Bolingbroke.

418
00:22:09.970 --> 00:22:11.470
Fellow, give place.

419
00:22:11.470 --> 00:22:12.800
Here is no longer stay.

420
00:22:12.800 --> 00:22:14.730
If thou love me, 'tis timethou wert away.

421
00:22:16.270 --> 00:22:19.870
What my tongue dares not,that my heart shall say.

422
00:22:35.930 --> 00:22:39.530
My lord, will it pleaseyou to fall to?

423
00:22:49.100 --> 00:22:54.130
Taste of it first, as thouart wont to do.

424
00:22:54.130 --> 00:22:56.770
My lord, I dare not.

425
00:22:56.770 --> 00:23:00.430
Sir Pierce of Exton, wholately came from the king,

426
00:23:00.430 --> 00:23:01.830
